Unless your shit is only like 250 words and the female has jack shit for characterization...

Bland self-inserts, male leads without names or meaningful personalities, are lazy and weaken the female lead by making the relationship unrealistic, one-directional, flat; that she fell in love with and spends the bulk of the story interacting with somebody who isn't interesting or alive. And yes I understand why you'd want a dry second person perspective, etc, but just keep it in mind that if it's not straight-up smut, most of the time you're crippling your protagonist (the furry).

It's like drawings that depicts the human as a sickly gray (>>12177753) or green skinned alopecia sufferer. Typically without eyes and whatnot. Good lord I know less-than-great artists sometimes draw something that can't help but remind the viewer of a cringey self-portrait, but when it's done well (pic related) it's so much more natural, atmospheric, relatable. Human.

If you're writing a story about a relationship and the reader is meant to bask in the warm feeling, it has to be a healthy relationship, and that means a back and forth. You also have to accept that no story will ever actually capture what it would be like if you, yes you the unique individual who has a first and last name and their own unique fingerprints, so you should make the move and put in as much love into the male as the female. Just make the human male likeable. make a male character that the reader will be rooting for. it'll get them involved. I promise.

It's horrible and I love it.

Have you ever had something that you keep going back to even though you know how trash it is? Well that Twokinds for me. Considering other webcomics out there, it's definitely not the worst, but it's writing is blah, the plot has very little direction, it's blatant fap-bait while also claiming not to be fap-bait, the characters are rather shallow a lot of the time, there are some oldy fetishy things going on all the time, and overall it's just not very good.
But I still read it.

I think the big issues is that the series is 14 years old, and Tom has grown up a lot since the beginning. Looking at stories that I've written over the course of 12 years, I see some of the same issues. The difference is that I work with four other people and we retcon dumb things whenever we realize that our teenage selves were idiots. Tom is just one person. He's one person who's written a successful webcomic and retconning things can be hard. The vestiges of his original style and worldbuilding haunt his current work (an example would be the setting map, it's kinda garbage). He refuses to engage certain topics beyond the base level which makes aspects of the comic look poorly thought out or lacking in depth. Now it is true, not everyone wants to have a fully fleshed out world, some people just want some pandering sex appeal and fetish-bait, and that's fine. Some things get decent amounts of development (and fan argument) like Natani's backstory and the effects of estrus in a "civilized" society but we gloss over some things. This is a world where humans are the only ones who can efficiently use magic, are also the best with technology and construction, where one of the major species has ultra-fast learning abilities but doesn't live to their third decade, where there are dragons out and about, and race-based slavery is common. You can't just write things like that into a story and not expect some reactions.
